{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539592"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:43:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:43:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16672"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16672"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.14,0.57,0.05,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9363"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66259"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9363"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16672"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51708"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1793"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4122"},{"type":"tags","id":"4123"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22160"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33595"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66259"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with three weeks of progressive lower abdominal pain and distension. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her last menstrual period was two weeks ago and she is not sexually active.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 118/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a firm, irregular mass arising from the pelvis extending to the umbilicus. Transvaginal ultrasound shows a 15 cm complex solid and cystic mass arising from the right ovary. Initial blood tests show cancer antigen 125 of 45 kU/L (0-35), carcinoembryonic antigen 2.1 \u00b5g/L (0-4.7), and cancer antigen 19-9 of 12 kU/L (0-37).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following combinations of tumour markers is most appropriate to now request?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cancer antigen 125, alpha-fetoprotein, cancer antigen 72-4","Alpha-fetoprotein, cancer antigen 125, human epidermal growth factor receptor 2","Lactate dehydrogenase, alpha-fetoprotein, beta-human chorionic gonadotropin","Lactate dehydrogenase, human epidermal growth factor receptor 2, cancer antigen 15.2","Beta-human chorionic gonadotropin, cancer antigen 125, human epidermal growth factor receptor 2"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis young woman presents with features highly suspicious for an ovarian germ cell tumour, given her age and the rapid onset of symptoms. The ultrasound findings of a complex solid and cystic mass are also consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactate dehydrogenase, alpha-fetoprotein, beta-human chorionic gonadotropin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate panel of tumour markers for suspected germ cell tumours. Different subtypes produce different markers: AFP is elevated in yolk sac tumours, BHCG in choriocarcinoma, and LDH in dysgerminoma. This combination allows for both diagnosis and monitoring of treatment response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECancer antigen 125, alpha-fetoprotein, cancer antigen 72-4\u003C/strong\u003E includes markers that are more appropriate for epithelial ovarian cancers. While CA125 and CA72-4 may be elevated in some ovarian cancers, they are not specific for germ cell tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-fetoprotein, cancer antigen 125, human epidermal growth factor receptor 2\u003C/strong\u003E includes markers used in different types of cancers. While AFP is relevant for germ cell tumours, HER2 is primarily used in breast cancer assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactate dehydrogenase, human epidermal growth factor receptor 2, cancer antigen 15.2\u003C/strong\u003E includes markers that are not specific for germ cell tumours. CA15.2 is primarily used in breast cancer monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-human chorionic gonadotropin, cancer antigen 125, human epidermal growth factor receptor 2\u003C/strong\u003E is an incomplete panel for germ cell tumours as it lacks AFP and LDH, which are essential for identifying specific subtypes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Germ cell tumours commonly present in young women with rapid onset of symptoms including abdominal pain and distension.","The initial tumour marker panel for suspected ovarian germ cell tumours should include alpha-fetoprotein (AFP), beta-human chorionic gonadotropin (BHCG), and lactate dehydrogenase (LDH).","Different histological subtypes of germ cell tumours produce different combinations of tumour markers, making the panel essential for diagnosis and monitoring."],"references":["Gic\u0103 N, Peltecu G, Chirculescu R, Gic\u0103 C, Stoicea MC, Serbanica AN, Panaitescu AM. Ovarian Germ Cell Tumors: Pictorial Essay. Diagnostics (Basel). 2022 Aug 24;12(9):2050. doi: 10.3390/diagnostics12092050. PMID: 36140449; PMCID: PMC9498179."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51708"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16672"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"d